BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260325T220000Z
DTEND:20260325T230000Z
DTSTAMP:20260325T000000Z
SUMMARY:Business Book Club - Becoming Trader Joe
DESCRIPTION:Do you have an interest in non-fiction books about business\, 
 finance\, economics\, or career development? Do you enjoy thoughtful 
 discussions with fellow entrepreneurs? Sign up for our Business Book Club 
 meeting! This month\, we'll be discussing "Becoming Trader Joe" by Joe 
 Coulombe and Patty Civalleri.\n\nBuild an iconic shopping experience that 
 your customers love and a work environment that your employees love being a 
 part of by using this blueprint from Trader Joe’s visionary founder\, Joe 
 Coulombe.\n\nInfuse your organization with a distinct personality and 
 culture that draws customers in a way that simply competing on price 
 cannot.\n\nJoe Coulombe founded what would become Trader Joe’s in the 
 late 1960s and helped shape it into the beloved\, quirky food chain it is 
 today. Realizing early on that he could not compete and win by playing the 
 same game his bigger competitors were playing\, he decided to build a store 
 for educated people of somewhat modest means. He brought in unusual 
 products from around the world and promoted them in the Fearless Flyer\, 
 providing customers with background on how they were sourced and their 
 nutritional value. He also gave the stores a tiki theme to reinforce the 
 exotic trader ship concept with employees wearing Hawaiian shirts.  \n\nIn 
 this way\, Joe laid down a blueprint for other business owners to follow to 
 build their own unique shopping experience that customers love\, and a work 
 environment that employees love being a part of. \n\nIn Becoming Trader 
 Joe\, Joe shares the lessons he learned by challenging the status quo and 
 rethinking the way a business operates. He shows readers of all 
 types:\n\nHow moving from a pure analytical approach to a more creative\, 
 problem-solving approach can drive innovation.\nHow finding an affluent 
 niche of passionate customers can be a better strategy than competing on 
 price and volume.\nHow questioning all aspects of the way you do business 
 leads to powerful results.\nHow to build a business around your values and 
 identity. \n\n \n\nBring your questions\, observations\, and reflections!
LOCATION:Meeting Room #4347\, Main Library (300 N. Roxboro St)
ORGANIZER;CN="Austin Daniels":MAILTO:ausdaniels@dconc.gov
CATEGORIES:Book Club, Business, Career Development
UID:LibCal-14288-16146456
URL:https://durhamcountylibrary.libcal.com/event/16146456
END:VEVENT
